{"name":"Clermont Scottish Ale", "source":"https://byo.com/cider/item/1756-clermont-scottish-ale", "description":"<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; color: #444444; font-family: georgia, serif; font-weight: bold;\"><em>\"This Scottish beer is named after the Clermont Sportsmen Club, of which I am a member. The club is located in the mountains of Clermont, Pennsylvania.\"&nbsp;<br /></em></p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; color: #444444; font-family: georgia, serif; font-weight: bold;\"><em>- Robert R. Heinlein</em></p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: georgia, serif;\"><strong>Step by Step</strong></p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: georgia, serif;\">Mash the base grains at 149&deg; F for 90 minutes. Sparge with three gallons of water at 168&deg; F. Add 2.5 gallons water to brew kettle. In separate sparge bags, add the crystal malts. Allow these grains to soak, without applying heat, while you conduct the mash. Remove specialty grains before the wort from the mash is added. Boil the wort for 90 minutes.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: georgia, serif;\">Add the first Tettnang hops at the beginning of the boil. Add the Northern Brewer hops halfway through the boil. Add the final two additions of Tettnang with 30 and 15 minutes left in the boil, respectively. Primary fermentation lasts for three days at 67&deg; F. Rack beer to secondary for 11 days at 45&deg; F. Keg, carbonate and serve.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "style":"14", "subtype":"A", "originalGravity":"1.032", "boilTime":"90", "maltAdditions":[{"pounds":2, "remainingMinutes":90, "triple":{"subject":"urn:uuid:a3004a89-6d1c-4a92-95d3-bea4ffd7c702", "predicate":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#addition", "object":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#pilsner